<Layout title="Section 8 – Medication Administration">
  <h1>Section 8: Medication Administration</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.8 – Performs Medication Administration</em></p>
  <p>
    Administer medications to adult patients using safe, person-centered practices based on
    medication error prevention principles.
  </p>

  <h2 id="rights">The Rights of Medication Administration</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Right</th><th>Verification</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Patient</strong></td><td>Use two identifiers (name + DOB or MRN); scan armband if using barcode MAR</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Drug</strong></td><td>Verify name, spelling, and purpose; clarify look-alike/sound-alike drugs</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Dose</strong></td><td>Recalculate; have second nurse verify high-alert medications</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Route</strong></td><td>Confirm ordered route is appropriate for patient condition</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Time</strong></td><td>Administer within 30-minute window of scheduled time</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Right Documentation</strong></td><td>Record immediately after administration; never chart in advance</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Additional Rights</strong>
    Some institutions add: Right to Refuse, Right Assessment, Right Education, and Right
    Evaluation — always use clinical judgment along with the core six rights.
  </div>

  <h2 id="error-prevention">Medication Error Prevention</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Never administer a medication you did not personally prepare.</li>
    <li>Do not administer a medication you cannot identify.</li>
    <li>Use the barcode medication administration (BCMA) system when available.</li>
    <li>Avoid distractions during medication preparation.</li>
    <li>Double-check calculations independently; use a second nurse for high-alert medications (heparin, insulin, chemotherapy).</li>
    <li>Report errors and near-misses through the facility's incident reporting system.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="routes">Routes of Administration</h2>
  <h3>Oral &amp; Enteral</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Most common route; convenient and cost-effective.</li>
    <li>Do not crush extended-release, enteric-coated, or sublingual tablets unless approved by pharmacist.</li>
    <li>For NG/PEG tube administration: flush before and after; administer medications separately.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Topical &amp; Transdermal</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Apply to clean, dry, intact skin; rotate sites to prevent irritation.</li>
    <li>Wear gloves when applying; remove previous patch/ointment before applying new dose.</li>
    <li>Nitroglycerin ointment: measure dose on paper; apply to non-hairy skin; document site.</li>
    <li>Estrogen patch: apply to lower abdomen or buttocks; rotate sites weekly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Ophthalmic &amp; Otic</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Eye drops: pull lower conjunctival sac down; instill drops in conjunctival sac, not directly on cornea.</li>
    <li>Ear drops (adults): pull pinna up and back to straighten ear canal; keep position for 5 minutes after instillation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Inhalation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Metered-dose inhaler (MDI):</strong> Shake; exhale; press and inhale slowly over 3–5 sec; hold breath 10 sec; spacer recommended.</li>
    <li><strong>Dry powder inhaler (DPI):</strong> Do not shake; load dose; inhale rapidly and deeply.</li>
    <li><strong>Nebulizer:</strong> Delivers medication as fine mist over 10–15 min; breathe normally through mouthpiece.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Parenteral — Injections</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Route</th><th>Needle Gauge/Length</th><th>Sites</th><th>Max Volume</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Intradermal (ID)</td><td>25–27G, 3/8–5/8"</td><td>Inner forearm, upper back</td><td>0.1 mL</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Subcutaneous (SQ)</td><td>25–31G, 3/8–5/8"</td><td>Abdomen, thigh, upper arm, upper back</td><td>1 mL</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intramuscular (IM)</td><td>20–23G, 1–1.5"</td><td>Ventrogluteal, deltoid, vastus lateralis</td><td>3 mL (deltoid 1 mL)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <ul>
    <li>Use Z-track technique for IM injections to prevent leakage and irritation.</li>
    <li>Do not recap used needles; dispose in sharps container immediately.</li>
    <li>Aspirate not required for SQ or most IM sites (current evidence-based practice).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Insulin Administration</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Use insulin syringes only (units marked); never substitute with other syringes.</li>
    <li>Rotate injection sites within the same anatomical region to ensure consistent absorption.</li>
    <li>Abdomen: fastest absorption; thigh: slowest; arm/buttock: intermediate.</li>
    <li>When mixing insulins: draw clear (regular/rapid-acting) before cloudy (NPH).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath – Chapters 31, 9)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Overview of Concepts in Pharmacology</li>
    <li>Principles of Safe Medication Administration</li>
    <li>Medication Administration: Assess, Analyze, Plan, Implement, Evaluate</li>
    <li>Medication and Its Use; Medication-Related Problems and Older Adults</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Readings</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Chapter 31, Medication Administration: pp. 624–708</li>
    <li>Chapter 9, Clinical Judgment to Promote Safe Medication Use: pp. 112–131</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Clinical Skills</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Administering Oral Medications</li>
    <li>Documenting Medication Administration</li>
    <li>Handling Medication Variations / Preventing Medication Errors</li>
    <li>Using Automated Medication Dispensing Systems</li>
    <li>Safe Handling of Hazardous Medications</li>
    <li>Applying Topical Medications; Estrogen Patch and Nitroglycerin Ointment</li>
    <li>Administering Eye and Ear Medications</li>
    <li>Using MDI, DPI, and Nebulized Medications</li>
    <li>Inserting Rectal Medication</li>
    <li>Preparing Injections from Ampule and Vial</li>
    <li>Preparing and Administering Insulin; Drawing up Multiple Types of Insulin</li>
    <li>Administering Intradermal, Subcutaneous, and Intramuscular Injections</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="key-terms">Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>BCMA:</strong> Barcode medication administration — system to verify patient and medication at point of care.</li>
    <li><strong>MAR:</strong> Medication Administration Record.</li>
    <li><strong>High-alert medication:</strong> Drug with significant risk of causing serious harm if used in error (e.g., insulin, heparin, chemotherapy).</li>
    <li><strong>Z-track:</strong> IM injection technique that displaces skin before injection to seal medication in muscle and prevent tracking.</li>
    <li><strong>IDM:</strong> Intradermal — used for allergy testing and TB (Mantoux) skin tests.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
